            <li>Thick ropes and cords</li>
            <li>Sturdy shoes</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="recovery">
        <h2>Recovery and Rebuilding</h2>
        <p>Remain calm, be alert, and awake. Listen to warnings of heavy and prolonged rainfall from the weather station. If your home is located below a debris-covered area, move to a safer place. Listen for sounds of rockfall, moving debris, and cracking trees.</p>
        <p>Call and help rescue teams, keep drinking water containers and a first aid kit, and avoid entering damaged houses. Watch for flooding if close to a river, help others who need assistance, especially elderly people, children, and women. Seek advice from local authorities for rebuilding damaged houses and roads. Report any damage to roads, power, and telephone lines to the concerned authorities.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="dos-and-donts">
        <h2>Do's & Don'ts</h2>
        <h3 id="dos">Do's</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Prepare tours to hilly regions according to weather department information.</li>
            <li>Move away from landslide paths or downstream valleys quickly.</li>
            <li>Keep drains clean.</li>
            <li>Inspect drains for litter, leaves, plastic bags, rubble, etc.</li>
            <li>Keep the weep holes open.</li>
            <li>Grow more trees that can hold the soil through roots.</li>
            <li>Identify areas of rock fall and subsidence, and move to safer areas.</li>
            <li>Listen for unusual sounds such as trees cracking or boulders knocking together.</li>
            <li>Stay alert, awake, and active during the impact or probability of impact.</li>
            <li>Locate and go to shelters.</li>
            <li>Try to stay with your family and companions.</li>
            <li>Check for injured and trapped persons.</li>
            <li>Mark paths of tracking to avoid getting lost.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 id="donts">Don'ts</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Avoid construction and staying in vulnerable areas.</li>
            <li>Do not panic and lose energy by crying.</li>
            <li>Do not touch or walk over loose material and electrical wiring or poles.</li>
            <li>Do not build houses near steep slopes and drainage paths.</li>
            <li>Do not drink contaminated water directly from rivers, springs, or wells.</li>
            <li>Do not move an injured person without rendering first aid unless the casualty is in immediate danger.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

   
